ntributions to the compendium history, Canada and Its Provinces (1913). Addressing a far larger audience, and treating a vastly enlarged body of Canadian literature, their work comes much closer to contemporary scholarship, with greater clarity, organization, and sheer bulk of information, but with the loss of some of the charm and assurance of Bourinot’s wide sweep. In further contrast to Bourinot’s determined biculturalism and will to unity, Roy and Marquis’ essays display vivid differences in the emotional allegiances and convictions of the founding cultures. Marquis starts by asking the question, ‘Has Canada a voice of her own in literature distinct from that of England?’; Roy treats French-Canadian literature in its Roman Catholic contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aFrench-Canadian literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBourinot, John George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLochhead, Douglas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMarquis, Thomas Guthrie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMarquis, Thomas Guthrie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoy, Camille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoy, Camille.1 aThomas, Clara.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144263230140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442632301423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442632301.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_E